{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 14:43:04.745252", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report — Clos EBGP fabric\\nDate: (now)\\n\\nExecutive summary\\n- Control plane (BGP): sessions between leaves, spines and super-spine are established and stable (neighbors Up, prefixes exchanged).\\n- Data plane: traffic from pc_0_0 (10.0.0.2) is being dropped/unreachable while other hosts (for example pc_0_1) can reach peers. The fault is localized to leaf_router_0_0.\\n- Root cause (most likely): an unintended static blackhole route for 10.0.0.0/30 installed on leaf_router_0_0. That more-specific blackhole overrides the /24 connected route and causes packets for 10.0.0.2 to be discarded.\\n\\nKey evidence and observations\\n\\n1) End-host reachability\\n- Composite reachability run shows many pairwise pings OK for hosts in the fabric, but hints of failure for pc_0_0:\\n  - Several pc_0_0 -> other hosts entries returned \"status\":\"unknown\" in the reachability summary (others like pc_0_1 show successful ping results).\\n  - Observed behavior: hosts in the 10.0.1.x and 10.1.x spaces are reachable among themselves; pc_0_0 shows limited/absent success.\\n\\n2) Host & leaf interface state\\n- pc_0_0 network config:\\n  - eth0: inet 10.0.0.2/24, default via 10.0.0.1 (so it uses leaf_router_0_0 as gateway).\\n- leaf_router_0_0 L2/L3:\\n  - eth4: inet 10.0.0.1/24 (connected to pc_0_0).\\n  - Counters: leaf shows RX packets 5, TX packets 1 on the 10.0.0.1 interface while pc_0_0 shows TX 5 RX 1 — consistent with leaf receiving packets from the host but not forwarding/responding properly.\\n\\n3) Routing table anomaly on leaf_router_0_0 (primary smoking gun)\\n- Route table excerpt from leaf_router_0_0:\\n  - \"blackhole 10.0.0.0/30 proto static metric 20\"\\n  - Also present: \"10.0.0.0/24 dev eth4 proto kernel scope link src 10.0.0.1\"\\n- Impact of the above:\\n  - The blackhole route (10.0.0.0/30) is a more specific route than the /24 and thus will match lookups for 10.0.0.2. Packets therefore match the blackhole and are dropped locally on the leaf instead of being routed via the connected interface.\\n\\n4) BGP control plane status (healthy overall)\\n- leaf_router_0_0 BGP summary:\\n  - All configured neighbors are Up; BGP messages are exchanged. Neighbor list shows four spine/super-spine neighbors with State/PfxRcd entries.\\n  - Example: neighbor 172.16.0.32 (AS 65100) Up and PfxRcd 7; similar for other neighbors.\\n- leaf_router_0_1 and spine routers show neighbors Up and prefixes exchanged (no session flaps).\\n- RIB/BGP tables sizes are small and consistent across routers, demonstrating control plane is functioning.\\n\\n5) Minor route-count inconsistencies (observed but secondary)\\n- The number of prefixes received by different neighbors varies slightly (e.g., leaf_router_0_0 PfxRcd 7 vs leaf_router_0_1 PfxRcd 8). This is consistent with the presence of a conflicting more-specific static route on leaf_router_0_0 (the blackhole) that prevents some prefixes / reachability from being used/installed in the local RIB the same way as on the other leaf.\\n- On leaf_router_0_1 there is a route entry referencing 10.0.0.0/30 via a BGP next-hop (nhid via 172.16.0.34). This indicates the /30 prefix exists in the network (advertised somewhere) or a remote advertisement of such a prefix; however on leaf_router_0_0 the same address space is locally blackholed.\\n\\nLocalization\\n- Fault is local to leaf_router_0_0:\\n  - The faulty route (blackhole) is present in leaf_router_0_0\\'s RIB.\\n  - pc_0_0 uses leaf_router_0_0 as gateway; traffic from pc_0_0 is observed reaching leaf (leaf RX count), but responses/forwarding do not occur (low TX count), consistent with local drop.\\n  - BGP sessions on the leaf are Up (so control plane is fine), which further indicates the issue is in the local RIB/static route rather than BGP neighbor/session failure.\\n\\nProbable root cause\\n- An incorrectly installed static blackhole route (10.0.0.0/30) on leaf_router_0_0 is the root cause of the observed loss for pc_0_0. The blackhole is more-specific than the connected /24 and therefore takes precedence, causing local blackholing of traffic destined to 10.0.0.0/30 addresses (which includes 10.0.0.2).\\n- How that blackhole got there: the route is marked as \"proto static\" in the RIB, which implies local configuration (manual static route or an automated/static route injection). There is also an indication that the /30 prefix is seen elsewhere via BGP on some routers, which may have led to a misconfiguration or attempted aggregation causing an unintended static blackhole on this leaf.\\n\\nImpact summary\\n- Host pc_0_0 (10.0.0.2) is effectively unreachable to other networks because its gateway (leaf_router_0_0) drops packets matching 10.0.0.0/30.\\n- BGP control plane remains healthy; other hosts and pods continue to exchange routes and forward traffic normally.\\n- Scope of impact: limited to traffic that relies on leaf_router_0_0 for forwarding (i.e., at least pc_0_0 / 10.0.0.0/24). Other pods/leaves/spines still have established BGP adjacencies.\\n\\nRelevant extracts (selected)\\n- leaf_router_0_0 ip route listing includes:\\n  - blackhole 10.0.0.0/30 proto static metric 20\\n  - 10.0.0.0/24 dev eth4 proto kernel scope link src 10.0.0.1\\n- leaf_router_0_0 interfaces:\\n  - eth4: inet 10.0.0.1/24 (connected to pc_0_0)\\n- pc_0_0 config:\\n  - eth0: inet 10.0.0.2/24, default via 10.0.0.1\\n- Reachability:\\n  - pc_0_1 <-> other hosts: pings OK\\n  - pc_0_0 -> some hosts: tests returned unknown / no successful responses\\n- BGP (leaf_router_0_0 show ip bgp summary):\\n  - Neighbors Up, PfxRcd values present (control plane stable)\\n\\nConclusion (diagnostic)\\n- The network\\'s BGP fabric and control plane are healthy; however there is a data-plane disruption for pc_0_0 caused by a local blackhole static route on leaf_router_0_0 (10.0.0.0/30). This blackhole is the most likely and direct cause of the observed host-level connectivity failures for 10.0.0.2. The problem is localized to leaf_router_0_0 and is not due to BGP adjacency flaps.\\n\\nNo mitigation steps are provided in this report (per instructions). If you want, I can next (on request) show the exact commands/lines to list (or remove) the offending static route and further verify traffic flow., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='854018d0-5fb3-4e49-a6e6-255d31d80072'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
